title: White-throated gerygone
alt_text: Fig 1. The bird(s) wound sticky threads around a Bougainvillea stem. These threads appeared to be spider web.

title: White-throated gerygone
alt_text: Fig 2. The nest was located in among the Bougainvillea foliage. Both sexes seemed to help build it.

title: White-throated gerygone
alt_text: Fig 3. Other material was then stuck to the sticky foundation. The birds did not work on the nest every day.

title: White-throated gerygone
alt_text: Fig 4. The weight of the nesting material and the gerygones gradually bent the branch vertical.

title: White-throated gerygone
alt_text: Fig 5. The nest took several weeks to build. It was made from strips of bark, twigs, animal fur, and manufactured fibres.

title: White-throated gerygone
alt_text: Fig 6. This view shows the circular entry to the nest.

title: White-throated gerygone
alt_text: Fig 7. This view shows the rear of the nest.

title: White-throated gerygone
alt_text: Fig 8. The gerygones abandoned the nest soon after completion. It may have been a decoy nest.
